lity]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Zaostrovskoye Rural Settlement of [[Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast|Primorsky District]], [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]], Russia. The population was 10 as of 2010.<ref name=\"arhangelskstat\">{{cite web|url=http://arhangelskstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/arhangelskstat/resources/2edc58004f857ef7ae20af9b972d8349/%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C.doc|website=arhangelskstat.gks.ru|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e \u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n\n{{ArkhangelskOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Oporno-Opytny Punkt\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u041f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Arkhangelsk Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast|Primorsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|64|28|N|40|27|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/arhangelskaya-oblast/primorskiy-rayon/derevnya-oporno-opitniy-punkt/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438 \u041e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u043e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442 \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Oporno-Opytny Punkt''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043f\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e-\u041e\u043f\u044b\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u041f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Zaostrovskoye Rural Settlement of [[Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast|Primorsky District]], [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]], Russia. The population was 10 as of 2010.<ref name=\"arhangelskstat\">{{cite web|url=http://arhangelskstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/arhangelskstat/resources/2edc58004f857ef7ae20af9b972d8349/%D1%87%D0%B8%D1%81%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C.doc|website=arhangelskstat.gks.ru|title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043f\u043e \u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043c \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438|accessdate=2019-02-19}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n\n\n{{ArkhangelskOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oporno-Opytny_Punkt"}
{"title_page": "Foveon X3 sensor", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n{{Update|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Foveon X3 sensor''' is an [[image sensor]] for use in digital cameras, designed by [[Foveon|Foveon, Inc.]] (now part of [[Sigma Corporation]]) and manufactured by Dongbu Electronics.<ref>\n[http://www.foveon.com/files/F13_Dongbu_PressRelease_final.pdf Foveon Announces New Image Sensor Manufacturing Partner: Dongbu Electronics of Seoul, South Korea]. Retrieved Jan. 18, 2014.</ref>\nIt uses an array of photosites, each of which consists of three vertically stacked [[photodiodes]], organised in a two-dimensional grid. Because different wavelengths of light penetrate silicon to different depths, each of the three stacked photodiodes has a different [[spectral sensitivity]] curve, allowing it to respond to different [[wavelength]]s of light.<ref name=\"Rush and Hubel\">{{cite journal|author=A. Rush|author2=P. Hubel|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/photogrst1964/66/1/66_1_57/_pdf|title=X3 Sensor Characteristics|journal=J. Soc. Photogr. Sci. Technol. Japan|date=2003|volume=66|issue=1|pages=57\u201360|access-date=March 6, 2007}}</ref> The signals from the three photodiodes are then processed, resulting in additive data for the three [[primary color|primary colour]]s: red, green, and blue.\n\nThe X3 sensor technology was first deployed in 2002 in the [[Sigma SD9]] [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|DSLR]] camera, and subsequently in the [[Sigma SD10|SD10]], [[Sigma SD14|SD14]], [[Sigma SD15|SD15]], [[Sigma SD1|SD1 (including SD1 Merrill)]], the compact [[Sigma DP2]] series from 2012, the [[Sigma dp2 Quattro]] series from 2014, and the [[Sigma SD Quattro]] series from 2016. The development of the Foveon X3 technology is the subject of the 2005 book ''The Silicon Eye'' by [[George Gilder]].\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:Absorption-X3.png|thumb|right|500px|Colour absorption in silicon and the Foveon X3 sensor. See text for explanation]]\n\nThe diagram to the right demonstrates how the Foveon X3 sensor works. Depicted on the left is the absorption of colours of the spectrum for each wavelength as they pass through the [[wafer (electronics)|silicon wafer]]. On the right, a Foveon X3 layered sensor stack is shown depicting the colours it detects at each absorption level for each output pixel. The sensor colours shown are only examples. In practice, the colour attributes of each output pixel using this sensor result from the camera's [[image processing]] algorithms that employ a matrix process to construct a single RGB colour from all of the data sensed by the photodiode stack.<ref name=\"Rush and Hubel\"/>\nIn terms of colour accuracy (sometimes referred to as a [[Metamerism (color)|metamerism index]]), the Foveon X3 was state of the art at the time of its invention.<ref>Paul M. Hubel, ''[http://www.foveon.com/files/CIC13_Hubel_Final.pdf Foveon Technology and the Changing Landscape of Digital Cameras]''; Richard F. Lyon and Paul M. Hubel, ''[http://www.foveon.com/files/CIC10_Lyon_Hubel_FINAL.pdf Eyeing the Camera: into the Next Century]'' (Santa Clara, California: [http://www.foveon.com/article.php?a=74 Foveon, Inc., X3 Technology \u2013 Technology Papers]). Retrieved May 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nBecause the depth in the silicon wafer of each of the three-layer Foveon X3 sensors is less than five [[micrometer]]s, it has a negligible effect on [[Focus (optics)|focusing]] or [[chromatic aberration]]. However, because the collection depth of the deepest sensor layer (red) is comparable to collection depths in other silicon [[CMOS]] and [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] sensors, some diffusion of electrons and loss of sharpness in the longer wavelengths occurs.<ref>{{cite thesis|author=Ji Soo Lee|url= http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~visor/pdf/JiSoo_Lee_PhD.pdf|title= Photoresponse of CMOS Image Sensors|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090219083724/http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~visor/pdf/JiSoo_Lee_PhD.pdf|archive-date=2009-02-19|url-status=dead|type=Ph.D. dissertation|publisher=University of Waterloo|date=2003}}</ref>\n\n==Utilisation==\nThe first digital camera to use a Foveon X3 sensor was the [[Sigma SD9]], a [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|digital SLR]] launched in 2002.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0202/02021104sigmads9.asp Digital Photography Review: 18 February 2002]</ref> This used a 2268x1512\u00d73 (3.54\u00d73 MP) iteration of the sensor, and was built on a Sigma-designed body using the [[Sigma SA mount]]. The camera was followed in 2003 by the improved but technically similar [[Sigma SD10]],<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/ Digital Photography Review: Sigma SD10: March 2004]</ref> which was in turn superseded in 2006 by the [[Sigma SD14]], which used a higher-resolution, 2640\u00d71760\u00d73 sensor. The successor, the [[Sigma SD15]], was released June 2010<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/1006/10061102sigmasd15available.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma UK to start shipping SD15 digital camera: 11 June 2010]</ref> using the same 2640\u00d71760\u00d73 (4.7\u00d73 MP) sensor as the SD14, and the [[Sigma SD1]] was released in June 2011<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.photographyblog.com/news/sigma_sd1_price_availability_announced/ |title=Sigma SD1 Price & Availability Announced |accessdate=2011-05-24}}</ref> with a new 4800\u00d73200\u00d73 sensor aimed at the professional market.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/1009/10092129sigmasd1.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma releases SD1 flagship digital SLR: 21 September 2010]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Polaroid Corporation]] announced the Polaroid x530,<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0402/04020909polaroidx530.asp Digital Photography Review: Polaroid x530: 09 February 2004]</ref> a compact camera with a 1408\u00d71056\u00d73, 1/1.8\" sensor. The camera received a limited release in 2005 but was recalled later in the year for unspecified image quality problems.<ref>[http://www.imaging-resource.com/NEWS/1113577444.html Imaging Resource: 15 April 2005]</ref> Sigma announced a prototype of their Foveon-based compact camera in 2006, the [[Sigma DP1]], using the same 14 MP sensor as the SD14 DSLR. A revised version of the prototype was exhibited in 2007, and the camera was eventually launched in Spring 2008.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0801/08013108sigmadp1.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma announces DP1 to be available spring 2008: 13 January 2008]</ref> Unlike the Polaroid x530, the DP1 had an [[APS-C]]-sized sensor, with a 28mm equivalent [[prime lens]]. The camera was subsequently revised as the DP1s and the DP1x. In 2009, the company launched the [[Sigma DP2|DP2]],<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0905/09051401sigmadp2availability.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma UK: DP2 now available: 14 May 2009]</ref> a compact camera using the same sensor and body as the DP1, but with a 41mm-equivalent f/2.8 lens.\n\nFoveon X3 sensors were also used in the Hanvision HVDUO-5M<ref>[http://www.alt-vision.com/hvduo5m.htm Hanvision: HVDUO-5M Digital Color Camera]</ref> and HVDUO-10M,<ref>[http://www.alt-vision.com/hvduo10m.htm Hanvision: HVDUO-10M Color Camera]</ref> a pair of digital cameras aimed at the scientific and industrial markets.\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors&nbsp;\u2013 operational differences==\nThe operation of the Foveon X3 sensor is quite different from that of the [[Bayer filter]] image sensor more commonly used in [[digital cameras]]. In the Bayer sensor, each photosite in the array consists of a single light sensor (either CMOS or CCD) that, as a result of filtration, is exposed to only one of the three primary colours, red, green, or blue. Constructing a full-colour image from a Bayer sensor requires [[demosaicing]], an [[Image scaling|interpolative process]] in which the output pixel associated with each photosite is assigned an [[RGB color model|RGB]] value based in part on the level of red, green, and blue reported by those photosites adjacent to it. The Foveon X3 sensor creates its RGB colour output for each photosite by combining the outputs of each of the stacked photodiodes at each of its photosites. This operational difference results in several significant consequences.\n\n===Colour artifacts===\nBecause demosaicing is not required for the Foveon X3 sensor to produce a full-colour image, the colour artifacts (\"coloured [[jaggies]]\") associated with that process are not seen. The separate anti-aliasing filter<ref>See, ''Optical anti-aliasing filter'' section of [[anti-aliasing filter]]</ref> commonly used<ref group=\"n\">Though its use is almost universal with Bayer sensors in digital cameras, it is not absolutely necessary. Kodak once produced two digital cameras, the [[Kodak DCS Pro SLR/n|DCS Pro SLR/n]] and DCS Pro SLR/c (''Digital Photography Review,'' [http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/kodakslrc/page2.asp Kodak DCS Pro SLR/c Review], June 2004, Retrieved March 3, 2007) using Bayer sensors without such a filter. However, [http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/kodakdcs14n/page22.asp significant [[moir\u00e9 pattern]]s were produced when photographing very fine detail]. Retrieved March 3, 2007.</ref> to mitigate those artifacts in a Bayer sensor is not required. This is because little [[aliasing]] occurs when the photodiodes for each colour, with the assistance of the [[microlens]]es, integrate the optical image over a region almost as big as the spacing of sensors for that colour.<ref group=\"n\">Microlenses are commonly used in all types of image sensors in digital cameras; in Bayer-filter sensors, microlenses allow the area of the optical image being averaged (integrated) per sample to approach 25% for red and blue and 50% for green, resulting in very little anti-aliasing, while for Foveon X3 sensors the area being averaged can approach 100% for each color, resulting in a significant anti-alias filter effect.</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Brian W. Keelan|title=Handbook of Image Quality: Characterization and Prediction|publisher=Marcel\u2013Dekker|year=2004|url= https://books.google.com/?id=E45MTZn17gEC&pg=RA1-PA388|isbn=0-8247-0770-2|page=390}}</ref> On the other hand, the method of colour separation by silicon penetration depth gives more cross-contamination between colour layers, meaning more issues with colour accuracy, especially in the red channel.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Light gathering and low-light performance===\nAnother difference is that more of the photons entering the camera will be detected by the Foveon X3 photosensor than is possible with a mosaic sensor. This is because each of the colour filters overlaying each photosite of a mosaic sensor passes only one of the primary colours, absorbing the other two. The absorption of these colours reduces the total amount of light gathered by the sensor and destroys much of the information about the colour of the light impinging on each sensor element. Although the Foveon X3 has a greater light-gathering ability, the individual layers do not respond as sharply to the respective colours. Thus colour-indicating information in the sensor's raw data requires \"aggressive\" matrix (essentially, removal of common-mode signals) to produce colour data in a standard [[color space|colour space]], which can increase colour noise in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auspiciousdragon.net/photowords/?p=880|title=Know raw? Part 2|date=2007-07-05|work=Photostream on auspiciousdragon.net|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928113408/http://www.auspiciousdragon.net/photowords/?p=880|archivedate=2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Spatial resolution===\nAccording to [[Sigma Corporation]], \"there has been some controversy in how to specify the number of [[pixel]]s in Foveon sensors.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.cameratown.com/news/news.cfm/hurl/id%7C3599|title=Sigma SD14 White Papers|access-date=2007-04-29}}\n</ref>\nThe argument has been over whether sellers should count the number of photosites or the total number of photodiodes, as a megapixel count, and whether either of those should be compared with the number of photodiodes in a [[Bayer filter]] sensor or camera as a measure of resolution.\n\nFor example, the dimensions of the photosite array in the sensor in the Sigma SD10 camera are 2268 \u00d7 1512, and the camera produces a native file size of those dimensions (times three colour layers). This amounts to approximately 3.4 million three-colour pixels. However, it has been advertised as a 10.2 MP camera by taking account of the fact that each photosite contains stacked red, green, and blue colour sensing photodiodes, or [[active pixel sensor|pixel sensors]] (2268 \u00d7 1512 \u00d7 3). By comparison, the dimensions of the photosite array in the 10.2 MP Bayer sensor in the Nikon D200 camera are 3872 \u00d7 2592, but there is only one photodiode, or one-pixel sensor, at each site. The cameras have equal numbers of photodiodes and produce similar RAW data file sizes, but the [[Bayer filter]] camera produces a larger native file size via [[demosaicing]].\n\nHowever, the actual resolution produced by the Bayer sensor is more complicated than the count of its photosites, or its native file size might suggest. The reason has to do with both the demosaicing and the separate anti-aliasing filter commonly used to reduce the occurrence or severity of colour [[moir\u00e9 pattern]]s that the mosaic characteristic of the Bayer sensor produces. The effect of this filter is to blur the image output of the sensor, thus producing a lower resolution than the photosite count would seem to imply. This filter is largely unnecessary with the Foveon X3 sensor and is not used. The earliest camera with a Foveon X3 sensor, the [[Sigma SD9]], showed visible luminance moir\u00e9 patterns, but not colour moir\u00e9.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/SigmaSD9/page23.asp|title=Sigma SD9 Review|work=DPReview|author=Phil Askey|date=November 2002}}\n</ref>\n\nSubsequent X3-equipped cameras have less aliasing because they include micro-lenses, which provide an effective{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} [[Anti-aliasing filter#Optical anti-aliasing filter|anti-aliasing filter]] by averaging the optical signal over an area commensurate with the sample density, which is not possible in any colour channel of a Bayer-type sensor. Aliasing from the Foveon X3 sensor is \"far less bothersome because it's monochrome\" according to Norman Koren.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.imatest.com/docs/print_sharpness.html|title=Sharpness: What is it and how is it measured?|work=Imatest docs|author=Norman Koren|access-date=2007-12-16}}\n</ref>\nTherefore, in theory, it is possible for a Foveon X3 sensor with the same number of photodiodes as a Bayer sensor and no separate anti-aliasing filter to attain a higher spatial resolution than that Bayer sensor. Independent tests indicate that the \"10.2 MP\" array of the Foveon X3 sensor (in the Sigma SD10) has a resolution similar to a 5 MP<ref>\n''Popular Photography & Imaging'', Vol. 69, No. 6 (June, 2005), (table on p. 47).\n</ref>\nor 6 MP<ref>\n[http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/page17.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma SD10 Review], March 2004, Retrieved March 3, 2007.\n</ref>\nBayer sensor, and at low [[film speed|ISO speed]] even similar to a 7.2 MP<ref>\nc|net Reviews, [http://reviews.cnet.com/Sigma_SD10/4505-6501_7-30588638.html Sigma SD10] Retrieved March 6, 2007.\n</ref>\nBayer sensor.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[Sigma SD14]], the 14 MP (4.7 MP red + 4.7 MP green + 4.7 MP blue) Foveon X3 sensor resolution is being compared favourably by reviewers to that of 10 MP Bayer sensors. For example, Mike Chaney of software says, \"the SD14 produces better photos than a typical 10 MP DSLR because it is able to carry sharp detail all the way to the 'falloff' point at 1700 LPI whereas contrast, colour detail, and sharpness begin to degrade long before the 1700 LPI limit on a Bayer based 10 MP DSLR.\"<ref>\n{{cite web | url = http://www.ddisoftware.com/sd14-5d/ | title = Sigma SD14 Resolution: 14 MP? 4.6 MP? How does the SD14 stack up against high-end cameras like the Canon EOD 5D? | author = Mike Chaney | year = 2007}}\n</ref>\nAnother article judges the Foveon X3 sensor as roughly equivalent to a 9 MP Bayer sensor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popphoto.com/howto/4276/foveon-x3-sensor-claims-put-to-the-test-color-resolution-vs-b-w-resolution-page2.html |title=Foveon X3 Sensor Claims Put to the Test |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205032245/http://www.popphoto.com/howto/4276/foveon-x3-sensor-claims-put-to-the-test-color-resolution-vs-b-w-resolution-page2.html |archivedate=February 5, 2008 }}\n</ref>\nA visual comparison between a 14 MP Foveon sensor and a 12.3 MP Bayer sensor shows Foveon has crisper details.<ref>\n{{cite web|author=Carl Rytterfalk|date=February 23, 2010|url=http://www.rytterfalk.com/2010/02/23/a-tiny-sigma-sd14-vs-nikon-d90-comparison/|title=A tiny Sigma SD14 vs Nikon D90 comparison..|website=Carl Rytterfalk Photography|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715011940/http://www.rytterfalk.com/2010/02/23/a-tiny-sigma-sd14-vs-Nikon-d90-comparison/|archive-date=2010-07-15|access-date=May 20, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors \u2013 noise==\nThe Foveon X3 sensor, as used in the Sigma SD10 camera, has been characterised by two independent reviewers as noisier than the sensors in some other DSLRs using the Bayer sensor at higher [[film speed|ISO film speed equivalents]],<ref>\nSee, ''e.g.'', c|net Reviews, [http://reviews.cnet.com/Sigma_SD10/4505-6501_7-30588638.html Sigma SD10] Retrieved March 6, 2007 and Steve's Digicams [http://www.steves-digicams.com/2003_reviews/sigma_sd10_pg7.html Sigma SD10 review] (November 28, 2003) Retrieved March 6, 2007.\n</ref>\nand specifically [[colorfulness|chroma]] noise has been noted.<ref>Camera Labs: [http://www.cameralabs.com/reviews/Sigma_DP1/sample_images.shtml Sigma DP1 Gallery]\n</ref><ref>\n[http://reviews.photographyreview.com/blog/sigma-dp1-review/ Sigma DP1 Review], photographyreview.com\n</ref>\nAnother has noted higher noise during long exposure times.<ref>Imaging Resource [http://www.imaging-resource.com/PRODS/SSD10/SD10A12.HTM Sigma SD10 review] (First posted 10-22-03.). Retrieved March 6, 2007.</ref><ref group=\"n\">This observation is consistent with a comparison of the images, displayed in Digital Photography Review, taken by the Sigma SD10 ([http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/page14.asp see here]) with those taken approximately contemporaneously of the same scene by the Bayer sensor-equipped Nikon D70 ([http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/nikond70 see here])/page15.asp. Both retrieved March 6, 2007.</ref> However, these reviewers offer no opinion as to whether this is an inherent property of the sensor or the camera's image processing algorithms.\n\nWith regards to the Sigma SD14 which uses a more recent Foveon X3 sensor, one reviewer judged its noise levels as ranging from \"very low\" at ISO 100 to \"Moderate\" at ISO 1600 when using the camera's [[Raw image format]].<ref>\n{{cite web | url =http://www.popphoto.com/gear/2008/12/camera-test-sigma-sd14 | title = Camera Test: Sigma SD14 | author = Michael J. McNamara|date=December 2008 |accessdate=June 6, 2013 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors \u2013 actual samples==\nSigma's [[Sigma SD14|SD14]] site has galleries of full-resolution images showing the color produced by the current state of Foveon technology. The 14-MP Foveon chip produces 4.7 MP native-size RGB files; 14-MP [[Bayer filter]] cameras produce a 14 MP native file size by interpolation (demosaicing). Direct visual comparison of images from 12.7-MP Bayer sensors and 14.1 MP Foveon sensors show Bayer images ahead on fine monochrome detail, such as the lines between bricks on a distant building, but the Foveon images are ahead on a colour resolution.<ref>\n{{cite web | title = Sigma SD14 Resolution: 14 MP? 4.6 MP? | author = Mike Chaney | date = March 16, 2007 | url = http://www.ddisoftware.com/sd14-5d/ | work = Digital Domain Inc.}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Color filter array|Colour filter array]]\n* [[Bayer filter]]\n* [[CYGM filter]]\n* [[RGBE filter]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Richard F. Lyon and Paul M. Hubel. [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.84.972&rep=rep1&type=pdf Eyeing the Camera: into the Next Century]. 10th Color Imaging Conference: Color Science, System and Applications. IS&T and SID, Springfield, Va, USA, 2002. P. 349\u2013355.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070218075729/http://www.sigma-sd14.com/sample-photo/index.html Sample gallery of Sigma SD14 with Foveon X3 sensor]\n*[http://www.foveon.com/article.php?a=67 Foveon X3 technology page]\n*[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0202/02021103foveonx3preview.asp DPReview Foveon X3 prototype preview]\n*[http://www.pbase.com/sigmadslr Sample Sigma/Foveon photos]\n*[http://www.digicamreview.co.uk/photos/gallery/polaroid_x530 Sample Polaroid x530/Foveon photos]\n*[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0609/06092604sigmadp1.asp Sigma DP1]\n\n{{Photography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foveon X3 Sensor}}\n[[Category:Digital photography]]\n[[Category:Image sensors]]\n[[Category:Color filter array]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=January 2020}}\n{{Update|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n{{use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\nThe '''Foveon X3 sensor''' is an [[image sensor]] for use in digital cameras, designed by [[Foveon|Foveon, Inc.]] (now part of [[Sigma Corporation]]) and manufactured by Dongbu Electronics.<ref>\n[http://www.foveon.com/files/F13_Dongbu_PressRelease_final.pdf Foveon Announces New Image Sensor Manufacturing Partner: Dongbu Electronics of Seoul, South Korea]. Retrieved Jan. 18, 2014.</ref>\nIt uses an array of photosites, each of which consists of three vertically stacked [[photodiodes]], organized in a two-dimensional grid. Because different wavelengths of light penetrate silicon to different depths, each of the three stacked photodiodes has a different [[spectral sensitivity]] curve, allowing it to respond to different [[wavelength]]s of light.<ref name=\"Rush and Hubel\">{{cite journal|author=A. Rush|author2=P. Hubel|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/photogrst1964/66/1/66_1_57/_pdf|title=X3 Sensor Characteristics|journal=J. Soc. Photogr. Sci. Technol. Japan|date=2003|volume=66|issue=1|pages=57\u201360|access-date=March 6, 2007}}</ref> The signals from the three photodiodes are then processed, resulting in additive data for the three [[primary color]]s: red, green, and blue.\n\nThe X3 sensor technology was first deployed in 2002 in the [[Sigma SD9]] [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|DSLR]] camera, and subsequently in the [[Sigma SD10|SD10]], [[Sigma SD14|SD14]], [[Sigma SD15|SD15]], [[Sigma SD1|SD1 (including SD1 Merrill)]], the compact [[Sigma DP2]] series from 2012, the [[Sigma dp2 Quattro]] series from 2014, and the [[Sigma SD Quattro]] series from 2016. The development of the Foveon X3 technology is the subject of the 2005 book ''The Silicon Eye'' by [[George Gilder]].\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:Absorption-X3.png|thumb|right|500px|Color absorption in silicon and the Foveon X3 sensor. See text for explanation]]\n\nThe diagram to the right demonstrates how the Foveon X3 sensor works. Depicted on the left is the absorption of colors of the spectrum for each wavelength as they pass through the [[wafer (electronics)|silicon wafer]]. On the right, a Foveon X3 layered sensor stack is shown depicting the colors it detects at each absorption level for each output pixel. The sensor colors shown are only examples. In practice, the color attributes of each output pixel using this sensor result from the camera's [[image processing]] algorithms that employ a matrix process to construct a single RGB color from all of the data sensed by the photodiode stack.<ref name=\"Rush and Hubel\"/>\nIn terms of color accuracy (sometimes referred to as a [[Metamerism (color)|metamerism index]]), the Foveon X3 was state of the art at the time of its invention.<ref>Paul M. Hubel, ''[http://www.foveon.com/files/CIC13_Hubel_Final.pdf Foveon Technology and the Changing Landscape of Digital Cameras]''; Richard F. Lyon and Paul M. Hubel, ''[http://www.foveon.com/files/CIC10_Lyon_Hubel_FINAL.pdf Eyeing the Camera: into the Next Century]'' (Santa Clara, California: [http://www.foveon.com/article.php?a=74 Foveon, Inc., X3 Technology \u2013 Technology Papers]). Retrieved May 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nBecause the depth in the silicon wafer of each of the three-layer Foveon X3 sensors is less than five [[micrometer]]s, it has a negligible effect on [[Focus (optics)|focusing]] or [[chromatic aberration]]. However, because the collection depth of the deepest sensor layer (red) is comparable to collection depths in other silicon [[CMOS]] and [[Charge-coupled device|CCD]] sensors, some diffusion of electrons and loss of sharpness in the longer wavelengths occurs.<ref>{{cite thesis|author=Ji Soo Lee|url= http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~visor/pdf/JiSoo_Lee_PhD.pdf|title= Photoresponse of CMOS Image Sensors|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090219083724/http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~visor/pdf/JiSoo_Lee_PhD.pdf|archive-date=2009-02-19|url-status=dead|type=Ph.D. dissertation|publisher=University of Waterloo|date=2003}}</ref>\n\n==Utilization==\nThe first digital camera to use a Foveon X3 sensor was the [[Sigma SD9]], a [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|digital SLR]] launched in 2002.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0202/02021104sigmads9.asp Digital Photography Review: 18 February 2002]</ref> This used a 2268x1512\u00d73 (3.54\u00d73 MP) iteration of the sensor, and was built on a Sigma-designed body using the [[Sigma SA mount]]. The camera was followed in 2003 by the improved but technically similar [[Sigma SD10]],<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/ Digital Photography Review: Sigma SD10: March 2004]</ref> which was in turn superseded in 2006 by the [[Sigma SD14]], which used a higher-resolution, 2640\u00d71760\u00d73 sensor. The successor, the [[Sigma SD15]], was released June 2010<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/1006/10061102sigmasd15available.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma UK to start shipping SD15 digital camera: 11 June 2010]</ref> using the same 2640\u00d71760\u00d73 (4.7\u00d73 MP) sensor as the SD14, and the [[Sigma SD1]] was released in June 2011<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.photographyblog.com/news/sigma_sd1_price_availability_announced/ |title=Sigma SD1 Price & Availability Announced |accessdate=2011-05-24}}</ref> with a new 4800\u00d73200\u00d73 sensor aimed at the professional market.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/1009/10092129sigmasd1.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma releases SD1 flagship digital SLR: 21 September 2010]</ref>\n\nIn 2004, [[Polaroid Corporation]] announced the Polaroid x530,<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0402/04020909polaroidx530.asp Digital Photography Review: Polaroid x530: 09 February 2004]</ref> a compact camera with a 1408\u00d71056\u00d73, 1/1.8\" sensor. The camera received a limited release in 2005 but was recalled later in the year for unspecified image quality problems.<ref>[http://www.imaging-resource.com/NEWS/1113577444.html Imaging Resource: 15 April 2005]</ref> Sigma announced a prototype of their Foveon-based compact camera in 2006, the [[Sigma DP1]], using the same 14 MP sensor as the SD14 DSLR. A revised version of the prototype was exhibited in 2007, and the camera was eventually launched in Spring 2008.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0801/08013108sigmadp1.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma announces DP1 to be available spring 2008: 13 January 2008]</ref> Unlike the Polaroid x530, the DP1 had an [[APS-C]]-sized sensor, with a 28mm equivalent [[prime lens]]. The camera was subsequently revised as the DP1s and the DP1x. In 2009, the company launched the [[Sigma DP2|DP2]],<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0905/09051401sigmadp2availability.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma UK: DP2 now available: 14 May 2009]</ref> a compact camera using the same sensor and body as the DP1, but with a 41mm-equivalent f/2.8 lens.\n\nFoveon X3 sensors were also used in the Hanvision HVDUO-5M<ref>[http://www.alt-vision.com/hvduo5m.htm Hanvision: HVDUO-5M Digital Color Camera]</ref> and HVDUO-10M,<ref>[http://www.alt-vision.com/hvduo10m.htm Hanvision: HVDUO-10M Color Camera]</ref> a pair of digital cameras aimed at the scientific and industrial markets.\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors&nbsp;\u2013 operational differences==\nThe operation of the Foveon X3 sensor is quite different from that of the [[Bayer filter]] image sensor more commonly used in [[digital cameras]]. In the Bayer sensor, each photosite in the array consists of a single light sensor (either CMOS or CCD) that, as a result of filtration, is exposed to only one of the three primary colors, red, green, or blue. Constructing a full-color image from a Bayer sensor requires [[demosaicing]], an [[Image scaling|interpolative process]] in which the output pixel associated with each photosite is assigned an [[RGB color model|RGB]] value based in part on the level of red, green, and blue reported by those photosites adjacent to it. The Foveon X3 sensor creates its RGB color output for each photosite by combining the outputs of each of the stacked photodiodes at each of its photosites. This operational difference results in several significant consequences.\n\n===Color artifacts===\nBecause demosaicing is not required for the Foveon X3 sensor to produce a full-color image, the color artifacts (\"colored [[jaggies]]\") associated with that process are not seen. The separate anti-aliasing filter<ref>See, ''Optical anti-aliasing filter'' section of [[anti-aliasing filter]]</ref> commonly used<ref group=\"n\">Though its use is almost universal with Bayer sensors in digital cameras, it is not absolutely necessary. Kodak once produced two digital cameras, the [[Kodak DCS Pro SLR/n|DCS Pro SLR/n]] and DCS Pro SLR/c (''Digital Photography Review,'' [http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/kodakslrc/page2.asp Kodak DCS Pro SLR/c Review], June 2004, Retrieved March 3, 2007) using Bayer sensors without such a filter. However, [http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/kodakdcs14n/page22.asp significant [[moir\u00e9 pattern]]s were produced when photographing very fine detail]. Retrieved March 3, 2007.</ref> to mitigate those artifacts in a Bayer sensor is not required. This is because little [[aliasing]] occurs when the photodiodes for each color, with the assistance of the [[microlens]]es, integrate the optical image over a region almost as big as the spacing of sensors for that color.<ref group=\"n\">Microlenses are commonly used in all types of image sensors in digital cameras; in Bayer-filter sensors, microlenses allow the area of the optical image being averaged (integrated) per sample to approach 25% for red and blue and 50% for green, resulting in very little anti-aliasing, while for Foveon X3 sensors the area being averaged can approach 100% for each color, resulting in a significant anti-alias filter effect.</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Brian W. Keelan|title=Handbook of Image Quality: Characterization and Prediction|publisher=Marcel\u2013Dekker|year=2004|url= https://books.google.com/?id=E45MTZn17gEC&pg=RA1-PA388|isbn=0-8247-0770-2|page=390}}</ref> On the other hand, the method of color separation by silicon penetration depth gives more cross-contamination between color layers, meaning more issues with color accuracy, especially in the red channel.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Light gathering and low-light performance===\nAnother difference is that more of the photons entering the camera will be detected by the Foveon X3 photosensor than is possible with a mosaic sensor. This is because each of the color filters overlaying each photosite of a mosaic sensor passes only one of the primary colors, absorbing the other two. The absorption of these colors reduces the total amount of light gathered by the sensor and destroys much of the information about the color of the light impinging on each sensor element. Although the Foveon X3 has a greater light-gathering ability, the individual layers do not respond as sharply to the respective colors. Thus color-indicating information in the sensor's raw data requires \"aggressive\" matrix (essentially, removal of common-mode signals) to produce color data in a standard [[color space]], which can increase color noise in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auspiciousdragon.net/photowords/?p=880|title=Know raw? Part 2|date=2007-07-05|work=Photostream on auspiciousdragon.net|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928113408/http://www.auspiciousdragon.net/photowords/?p=880|archivedate=2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===Spatial resolution===\nAccording to [[Sigma Corporation]], \"there has been some controversy in how to specify the number of [[pixel]]s in Foveon sensors.\"<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.cameratown.com/news/news.cfm/hurl/id%7C3599|title=Sigma SD14 White Papers|access-date=2007-04-29}}\n</ref>\nThe argument has been over whether sellers should count the number of photosites or the total number of photodiodes, as a megapixel count, and whether either of those should be compared with the number of photodiodes in a [[Bayer filter]] sensor or camera as a measure of resolution.\n\nFor example, the dimensions of the photosite array in the sensor in the Sigma SD10 camera are 2268 \u00d7 1512, and the camera produces a native file size of those dimensions (times three color layers). This amounts to approximately 3.4 million three-color pixels. However, it has been advertised as a 10.2 MP camera by taking account of the fact that each photosite contains stacked red, green, and blue color sensing photodiodes, or [[active pixel sensor|pixel sensors]] (2268 \u00d7 1512 \u00d7 3). By comparison, the dimensions of the photosite array in the 10.2 MP Bayer sensor in the Nikon D200 camera are 3872 \u00d7 2592, but there is only one photodiode, or one-pixel sensor, at each site. The cameras have equal numbers of photodiodes and produce similar RAW data file sizes, but the [[Bayer filter]] camera produces a larger native file size via [[demosaicing]].\n\nHowever, the actual resolution produced by the Bayer sensor is more complicated than the count of its photosites, or its native file size might suggest. The reason has to do with both the demosaicing and the separate anti-aliasing filter commonly used to reduce the occurrence or severity of color [[moir\u00e9 pattern]]s that the mosaic characteristic of the Bayer sensor produces. The effect of this filter is to blur the image output of the sensor, thus producing a lower resolution than the photosite count would seem to imply. This filter is largely unnecessary with the Foveon X3 sensor and is not used. The earliest camera with a Foveon X3 sensor, the [[Sigma SD9]], showed visible luminance moir\u00e9 patterns, but not color moir\u00e9.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/SigmaSD9/page23.asp|title=Sigma SD9 Review|work=DPReview|author=Phil Askey|date=November 2002}}\n</ref>\n\nSubsequent X3-equipped cameras have less aliasing because they include micro-lenses, which provide an effective{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} [[Anti-aliasing filter#Optical anti-aliasing filter|anti-aliasing filter]] by averaging the optical signal over an area commensurate with the sample density, which is not possible in any color channel of a Bayer-type sensor. Aliasing from the Foveon X3 sensor is \"far less bothersome because it's monochrome\" according to Norman Koren.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.imatest.com/docs/print_sharpness.html|title=Sharpness: What is it and how is it measured?|work=Imatest docs|author=Norman Koren|access-date=2007-12-16}}\n</ref>\nTherefore, in theory, it is possible for a Foveon X3 sensor with the same number of photodiodes as a Bayer sensor and no separate anti-aliasing filter to attain a higher spatial resolution than that Bayer sensor. Independent tests indicate that the \"10.2 MP\" array of the Foveon X3 sensor (in the Sigma SD10) has a resolution similar to a 5 MP<ref>\n''Popular Photography & Imaging'', Vol. 69, No. 6 (June, 2005), (table on p. 47).\n</ref>\nor 6 MP<ref>\n[http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/page17.asp Digital Photography Review: Sigma SD10 Review], March 2004, Retrieved March 3, 2007.\n</ref>\nBayer sensor, and at low [[film speed|ISO speed]] even similar to a 7.2 MP<ref>\nc|net Reviews, [http://reviews.cnet.com/Sigma_SD10/4505-6501_7-30588638.html Sigma SD10] Retrieved March 6, 2007.\n</ref>\nBayer sensor.\n\nWith the introduction of the [[Sigma SD14]], the 14 MP (4.7 MP red + 4.7 MP green + 4.7 MP blue) Foveon X3 sensor resolution is being compared favorably by reviewers to that of 10 MP Bayer sensors. For example, Mike Chaney of software says, \"the SD14 produces better photos than a typical 10 MP DSLR because it is able to carry sharp detail all the way to the 'falloff' point at 1700 LPI whereas contrast, color detail, and sharpness begin to degrade long before the 1700 LPI limit on a Bayer based 10 MP DSLR.\"<ref>\n{{cite web | url = http://www.ddisoftware.com/sd14-5d/ | title = Sigma SD14 Resolution: 14 MP? 4.6 MP? How does the SD14 stack up against high-end cameras like the Canon EOD 5D? | author = Mike Chaney | year = 2007}}\n</ref>\nAnother article judges the Foveon X3 sensor as roughly equivalent to a 9 MP Bayer sensor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popphoto.com/howto/4276/foveon-x3-sensor-claims-put-to-the-test-color-resolution-vs-b-w-resolution-page2.html |title=Foveon X3 Sensor Claims Put to the Test |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080205032245/http://www.popphoto.com/howto/4276/foveon-x3-sensor-claims-put-to-the-test-color-resolution-vs-b-w-resolution-page2.html |archivedate=February 5, 2008 }}\n</ref>\nA visual comparison between a 14 MP Foveon sensor and a 12.3 MP Bayer sensor shows Foveon has crisper details.<ref>\n{{cite web|author=Carl Rytterfalk|date=February 23, 2010|url=http://www.rytterfalk.com/2010/02/23/a-tiny-sigma-sd14-vs-nikon-d90-comparison/|title=A tiny Sigma SD14 vs Nikon D90 comparison..|website=Carl Rytterfalk Photography|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715011940/http://www.rytterfalk.com/2010/02/23/a-tiny-sigma-sd14-vs-Nikon-d90-comparison/|archive-date=2010-07-15|access-date=May 20, 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors \u2013 noise==\nThe Foveon X3 sensor, as used in the Sigma SD10 camera, has been characterized by two independent reviewers as noisier than the sensors in some other DSLRs using the Bayer sensor at higher [[film speed|ISO film speed equivalents]],<ref>\nSee, ''e.g.'', c|net Reviews, [http://reviews.cnet.com/Sigma_SD10/4505-6501_7-30588638.html Sigma SD10] Retrieved March 6, 2007 and Steve's Digicams [http://www.steves-digicams.com/2003_reviews/sigma_sd10_pg7.html Sigma SD10 review] (November 28, 2003) Retrieved March 6, 2007.\n</ref>\nand specifically [[colorfulness|chroma]] noise has been noted.<ref>Camera Labs: [http://www.cameralabs.com/reviews/Sigma_DP1/sample_images.shtml Sigma DP1 Gallery]\n</ref><ref>\n[http://reviews.photographyreview.com/blog/sigma-dp1-review/ Sigma DP1 Review], photographyreview.com\n</ref>\nAnother has noted higher noise during long exposure times.<ref>Imaging Resource [http://www.imaging-resource.com/PRODS/SSD10/SD10A12.HTM Sigma SD10 review] (First posted 10-22-03.). Retrieved March 6, 2007.</ref><ref group=\"n\">This observation is consistent with a comparison of the images, displayed in Digital Photography Review, taken by the Sigma SD10 ([http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/sigmasd10/page14.asp see here]) with those taken approximately contemporaneously of the same scene by the Bayer sensor-equipped Nikon D70 ([http://www.dpreview.com/reviews/nikond70 see here])/page15.asp. Both retrieved March 6, 2007.</ref> However, these reviewers offer no opinion as to whether this is an inherent property of the sensor or the camera's image processing algorithms.\n\nWith regards to the Sigma SD14 which uses a more recent Foveon X3 sensor, one reviewer judged its noise levels as ranging from \"very low\" at ISO 100 to \"Moderate\" at ISO 1600 when using the camera's [[Raw image format]].<ref>\n{{cite web | url =http://www.popphoto.com/gear/2008/12/camera-test-sigma-sd14 | title = Camera Test: Sigma SD14 | author = Michael J. McNamara|date=December 2008 |accessdate=June 6, 2013 }}\n</ref>\n\n==Comparison to Bayer filter sensors \u2013 actual samples==\nSigma's [[Sigma SD14|SD14]] site has galleries of full-resolution images showing the color produced by the current state of Foveon technology. The 14-MP Foveon chip produces 4.7 MP native-size RGB files; 14-MP [[Bayer filter]] cameras produce a 14 MP native file size by interpolation (demosaicing). Direct visual comparison of images from 12.7-MP Bayer sensors and 14.1 MP Foveon sensors show Bayer images ahead on fine monochrome detail, such as the lines between bricks on a distant building, but the Foveon images are ahead on a color resolution.<ref>\n{{cite web | title = Sigma SD14 Resolution: 14 MP? 4.6 MP? | author = Mike Chaney | date = March 16, 2007 | url = http://www.ddisoftware.com/sd14-5d/ | work = Digital Domain Inc.}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Color filter array]]\n* [[Bayer filter]]\n* [[CYGM filter]]\n* [[RGBE filter]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* Richard F. Lyon and Paul M. Hubel. [http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.84.972&rep=rep1&type=pdf Eyeing the Camera: into the Next Century]. 10th Color Imaging Conference: Color Science, System and Applications. IS&T and SID, Springfield, Va, USA, 2002. P. 349\u2013355.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070218075729/http://www.sigma-sd14.com/sample-photo/index.html Sample gallery of Sigma SD14 with Foveon X3 sensor]\n*[http://www.foveon.com/article.php?a=67 Foveon X3 technology page]\n*[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0202/02021103foveonx3preview.asp DPReview Foveon X3 prototype preview]\n*[http://www.pbase.com/sigmadslr Sample Sigma/Foveon photos]\n*[http://www.digicamreview.co.uk/photos/gallery/polaroid_x530 Sample Polaroid x530/Foveon photos]\n*[http://www.dpreview.com/news/0609/06092604sigmadp1.asp Sigma DP1]\n\n{{Photography}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foveon X3 Sensor}}\n[[Category:Digital photography]]\n[[Category:Image sensors]]\n[[Category:Color filter array]]\n", "name_user": "RedPufferfish", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected spelling and grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foveon_X3_sensor"}
{"title_page": "Raquel Murillo", "text_new": "{{Infobox character\n| colour           = #900\n| image            = Raquel Murillo.jpg\n| caption          = \n| name             = Raquel Murillo\n| full_name        = \n| portrayer        = [[Itziar Itu\u00f1o]]\n| series           = [[Money Heist]]\n| first            = \"[[List_of_Money_Heist_episodes#Part_1|Do as Planned]]\" (2017)\n| last             = \"[[List_of_Money_Heist_episodes#Part_4|The Paris Plan]]\" (2020)\n| alias            = Lisbon\n| creator          = [[\u00c1lex Pina]]\n| occupation       = Inspector<br>Robber\n| children         = Paula Vicu\u00f1a Murillo (daughter)\n| spouse           = Alberto Vicu\u00f1a (ex-husbamd)\n| relatives        = Mariv\u00ed Fuentes (mother)\n| affiliation      = \n| fighting_style   = \n| weapon           = \n| family           = \n| nationality      = Spanish\n}}\n'''Raquel Murillo''' ('''Lisbon''') is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Money Heist]]'', portrayed by [[Itziar Itu\u00f1o]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antena3.com/series/casa-de-papel/personajes/itziar-ituno-raquel-inspectora-murillo_2017033158de70db0cf2abec9e0172fc.html|title=PERSONAJES 'LA CASA DE PAPEL' - LOS ATRACADORES - Itziar Itu\u00f1o es Raquel Murillo|language=es|publisher=antena3.com|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In the TV show she is a main character, she an inspector of the [[National Police Corps]] who is put in charge of the case until she joins the group in part 3.\n\n==The character==\nRaquel Murillo is an [[inspector]] of the [[National Police Corps|Spanish police]] charged with negotiating with thieves (seasons 1 and 2). However, during the [[negotiations]], she met [[Professor (Money Heist)|the Professor]], who introduced himself to her in a bar with the name of Salvador Martin, embarked on a relationship with him and fell in love with him to the point of choosing to follow him instead of arresting him. and at that point he becomes an effective member of the gang and, like them, takes the name of a city: Lisbon (seasons 3 and 4).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1265024/money-heist-explained-why-did-lisbon-go-bank-of-spain-professor-netflix-season-4|title=Money Heist explained: Why did Lisbon go into the Bank of Spain?|publisher=express.co.uk|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6468322/characters/nm1523587?ref_=tt_cl_t3 Raquel Murillo] on [[IMDb]]\n\n<!--\n{{Money Heist}}\n-->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raquel Murillo}}\n[[Category:Money Heist characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2017]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox character\n| colour           = #900\n| image            = Raquel Murillo.jpg\n| caption          = \n| name             = Raquel Murillo\n| full_name        = \n| portrayer        = [[Itziar Itu\u00f1o]]\n| series           = [[Money Heist]]\n| first            = \"[[List_of_Money_Heist_episodes#Part_1|Do as Planned]]\" (2017)\n| last             = \"[[List_of_Money_Heist_episodes#Part_4|The Paris Plan]]\" (2020)\n| alias            = Lisbon\n| creator          = [[\u00c1lex Pina]]\n| occupation       = Inspector<br>Robber\n| children         = Paula Vicu\u00f1a Murillo (daughter)\n| spouse           = Alberto Vicu\u00f1a (ex-husbamd)\n| relatives        = Mariv\u00ed Fuentes (mother)\n| affiliation      = \n| fighting_style   = \n| weapon           = \n| family           = \n| nationality      = Spanish\n}}\n'''Raquel Murillo''' ('''Lisbon''') is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Money Heist]]'', portrayed by [[Itziar Itu\u00f1o]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antena3.com/series/casa-de-papel/personajes/itziar-ituno-raquel-inspectora-murillo_2017033158de70db0cf2abec9e0172fc.html|title=PERSONAJES 'LA CASA DE PAPEL' - LOS ATRACADORES - Itziar Itu\u00f1o es Raquel Murillo|language=es|publisher=antena3.com|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> In the TV show she is a main character, she an inspector of the [[National Police Corps]] who is put in charge of the case until she joins the group in part 3.\n\n==The character==\nRaquel Murillo is an [[inspector]] of the [[National Police Corps|Spanish police]] charged with negotiating with thieves (seasons 1 and 2). However, during the [[negotiations]], he met [[Professor (Money Heist)|the Professor]], who introduced himself to her in a bar with the name of Salvador Martin, embarked on a relationship with him and fell in love with him to the point of choosing to follow him instead of arresting him. and at that point he becomes an effective member of the gang and, like them, takes the name of a city: Lisbon (seasons 3 and 4).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1265024/money-heist-explained-why-did-lisbon-go-bank-of-spain-professor-netflix-season-4|title=Money Heist explained: Why did Lisbon go into the Bank of Spain?|publisher=express.co.uk|accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6468322/characters/nm1523587?ref_=tt_cl_t3 Raquel Murillo] on [[IMDb]]\n\n<!--\n{{Money Heist}}\n-->\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raquel Murillo}}\n[[Category:Money Heist characters]]\n[[Category:Female characters in television]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2017]]\n", "name_user": "Kasper2006", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe character", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raquel_Murillo"}
{"title_page": "Odinochka", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Odinochka\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0430\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Arkhangelsk Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast|Primorsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|64|35|N|40|26|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/arhangelskaya-oblast/primorskiy-rayon/derevnya-odinochka/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0438 \u041e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Odinochka''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0447\u043a\u0430}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Ostrovnoye Rural Settlement of [[Primorsky District, Arkhangelsk Oblast|Primorsky District]], [[Arkhangelsk Oblast]], Russia. The population was 41 as of 2010.<ref name=\"arhangelskstat\